%[text] # Model Architecture
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_0fea] Copyright 2026 The MathWorks, Inc.
%[text] ## System Overview
%[text] The model represents a 10 MW double conversion UPS system operating at 480 V AC on the grid side and 800 V DC on the internal bus. The system consists of three parallel UPS modules, each rated at 5 MW, operating in an N+1 configuration and implemented using averaged-value models with a 50 µs timestep.
%[text]  ![](text:image:8c0a)
%[text] 
%[text] Power is continuously processed through the rectifier, DC-link, and inverter. The inverter always supplies the load, while the DC bus remains continuously energized. The rectifier and battery together maintain this DC bus under all operating conditions.
%[text] The model also includes a backup generator that supports the system when the main grid is unavailable for extended duration. The battery provides immediate support during grid loss, while the generator ramps up and takes over as the long-term power source. 
%[text] ### Active Front End Rectifier
%[text] The active front end rectifier is a three-phase voltage source converter operating in grid-following mode. It regulates the DC bus voltage under normal grid conditions and draws sinusoidal current from the grid.
%[text] The control is implemented in dq frame with a dual-loop structure. An outer voltage loop generates the d-axis current reference, while inner current loops track Id and Iq and produce modulation signals.
%[text] The rectifier inherently performs power factor correction by aligning input current with the PCC voltage and maintaining near-zero reactive current. This ensures near-unity power factor and low harmonic distortion.
%[text] When the grid is degraded or unavailable, the rectifier contribution reduces and control of the DC bus is transferred to the battery.
%[text] ### DC Bus
%[text] The DC bus is the central energy node of the system. It receives power from the rectifier, exchanges energy with the battery, and supplies the inverter. The DC bus capacitance provides short-term energy buffering, limiting voltage deviations during load transients and enabling smooth transitions between operating modes.
%[text]  ![](text:image:3ff6)
%[text] ### Battery Supervisory Control and Mode Transitions
%[text] The battery is controlled by a Stateflow supervisor that manages transitions between charging, float, and discharge modes. The controller monitors SOC, battery voltage, DC-link voltage, PCC voltage, and protection signals to determine the operating state.
%[text]  ![](text:image:6b61)
%[text] 
%[text] The system starts in standby and transitions into one of the following states:
%[text] - **Standby** : Initialization state where operating conditions are evaluated.
%[text] - **Constant current charging** : Activated when SOC is low. The battery charges at a fixed current while the rectifier maintains the DC bus.
%[text] - **Constant voltage charging** : Triggered when battery voltage reaches its limit. Voltage is regulated while current tapers.
%[text] - **Float charging** : Maintains the battery at nominal voltage with minimal current once fully charged.
%[text] - **Discharge** : Activated when PCC voltage drops below threshold or the rectifier is unavailable. The battery supplies the DC bus and supports the full inverter load. \
%[text] During normal grid-connected operation, the rectifier regulates the DC bus and the battery operates in charging or float mode. In this condition, the battery operates in a droop response mode, where its current contribution is proportional to DC voltage deviation. This allows the battery to support the DC bus without interfering with the rectifier control loop, similar to low-voltage ride-through behavior.
%[text] When grid conditions weaken, DC voltage deviations increase and the battery injects current to support the DC bus. When the grid is lost, the rectifier output drops to zero and the system transitions to discharge mode. The battery then switches from droop behavior to active voltage regulation and supplies the full inverter demand.
%[text] Since the battery can only sustain the load for a limited duration, the generator is started during this period. The battery maintains the DC bus until the generator reaches steady operation.
%[text] When the generator becomes available, it powers the rectifier, which resumes DC bus regulation. The battery then transitions back through the charging sequence before returning to float mode.
%[text] All transitions are filtered using duration conditions to prevent rapid switching during transients.
%[text] ### Output Inverter and Parallel Operation
%[text] The output inverter operates in grid-forming mode and supplies the IT load with regulated voltage and frequency. Three inverter modules, each rated at 5 MW, operate in parallel to supply the total load with N+1 redundancy.
%[text] Each inverter implements droop control to enable decentralized load sharing:
%[text] - active power is regulated through frequency droop
%[text] - reactive power is regulated through voltage droop \
%[text] This allows proportional sharing of load between the modules without requiring communication. Under balanced conditions, each module contributes equally. If one module is unavailable, the remaining modules automatically increase their output to maintain supply.
%[text] To improve stability and reduce circulating currents between parallel inverters, virtual impedance is implemented. This ensures that small differences in module voltages do not result in unwanted circulating power.
%[text] Because the inverter is always connected to the DC bus, it remains unaffected by upstream disturbances. During transitions between grid, battery, and generator operation, the inverter continues supplying the load without interruption.

